WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.144
Welcome to a Deep Dive episode. Today I'm going over

00:00:04.144 --> 00:00:08.289
what actually matters in Google's Gemma four release — cutting

00:00:08.289 --> 00:00:12.433
through the benchmark noise to what's genuinely significant about this

00:00:12.433 --> 00:00:16.578
open-weights model family. Google dropped Gemma four on April second,

00:00:16.578 --> 00:00:20.723
and for once the open-weights release cycle is moving faster

00:00:20.723 --> 00:00:24.867
than the hype cycle can catch up. I've spent the

00:00:24.867 --> 00:00:29.012
last couple of days working through the technical docs, running

00:00:29.012 --> 00:00:33.156
the models locally, and reading the community reaction. Here's what

00:00:33.156 --> 00:00:37.300
I actually think. The short version: Gemma four is a

00:00:37.300 --> 00:00:41.445
genuinely capable model family. But the headline isn't a benchmark

00:00:41.445 --> 00:00:45.590
number. It's a license. Apache two-point-zero — no asterisks, no

00:00:45.590 --> 00:00:49.734
carve-outs, no monthly active user cap tucked into a Terms

00:00:49.734 --> 00:00:53.878
of Use P-D-F. That's the thing that will matter in

00:00:53.878 --> 00:00:58.023
six months, not whether the thirty-one billion parameter model scores

00:00:58.023 --> 00:01:02.168
zero point three points higher than Qwen on G-P-Q-A Diamond.

00:01:02.168 --> 00:01:06.312
Let's get into it. The Model Lineup. Four models, two

00:01:06.312 --> 00:01:10.456
design philosophies. Google calls them the edge tier and the

00:01:10.456 --> 00:01:14.601
workstation tier, and the distinction is real — these aren't

00:01:14.601 --> 00:01:18.746
just different sizes of the same thing. The edge models

00:01:18.746 --> 00:01:22.890
are called E-two-B and E-four-B. The "E" stands for "effective"

00:01:22.890 --> 00:01:27.035
— Google's shorthand for Per-Layer Embeddings, or P-L-E. The idea:

00:01:27.035 --> 00:01:31.179
rather than just having one embedding table at the input,

00:01:31.179 --> 00:01:35.323
P-L-E adds a second embedding table that feeds a small

00:01:35.323 --> 00:01:39.468
residual signal into every decoder layer. The result is that

00:01:39.468 --> 00:01:43.612
a four-point-five billion effective-parameter model gets representational depth well beyond

00:01:43.612 --> 00:01:47.757
its actual weight count. On quality-per-size benchmarks, it shows. The

00:01:47.757 --> 00:01:51.901
E-two-B has two point three billion effective parameters — five

00:01:51.901 --> 00:01:56.046
point one billion total — with a one hundred twenty-eight

00:01:56.046 --> 00:02:00.191
thousand token context window. The E-four-B has four point five

00:02:00.191 --> 00:02:04.335
billion effective parameters — eight billion total — also with

00:02:04.335 --> 00:02:08.480
a one hundred twenty-eight thousand token context window. The workstation

00:02:08.480 --> 00:02:12.624
tier has two entries. The twenty-six billion model is a

00:02:12.624 --> 00:02:16.768
Mixture of Experts architecture — M-o-E — with only four

00:02:16.768 --> 00:02:20.913
billion parameters active during inference. You get the quality of

00:02:20.913 --> 00:02:25.058
a large model at the compute cost of a much

00:02:25.058 --> 00:02:29.202
smaller one, in theory. More on the catch in a

00:02:29.202 --> 00:02:33.346
moment. The thirty-one billion dense model is a straightforward full-parameter

00:02:33.346 --> 00:02:37.491
model with a two hundred fifty-six thousand token context window.

00:02:37.491 --> 00:02:41.635
Two notable absences: there's no replacement for Gemma three's popular

00:02:41.635 --> 00:02:45.780
twelve billion parameter model, leaving an awkward gap between about

00:02:45.780 --> 00:02:49.924
four point five billion effective and twenty-six billion. And the

00:02:49.924 --> 00:02:54.069
rumored one hundred twenty billion flagship that pre-release chatter anticipated

00:02:54.069 --> 00:02:58.213
didn't materialize at launch. Architecture and Benchmarks. Let me walk

00:02:58.213 --> 00:03:02.358
through the three architectural moves worth understanding. First: Alternating Attention.

00:03:02.358 --> 00:03:06.502
Rather than running full attention through every layer, Gemma four

00:03:06.502 --> 00:03:10.647
alternates between local sliding-window attention and global full-context attention. Local

00:03:10.647 --> 00:03:14.792
layers use five hundred twelve token windows on smaller models,

00:03:14.792 --> 00:03:18.936
one thousand twenty-four token windows on larger ones. The final

00:03:18.936 --> 00:03:23.081
layer is always global. This is substantially more compute-efficient than

00:03:23.081 --> 00:03:27.225
dense full attention throughout — it's how you get to

00:03:27.225 --> 00:03:31.370
two hundred fifty-six thousand token context windows without proportional cost

00:03:31.370 --> 00:03:35.514
blowup. Second: Dual R-o-P-E. Standard rotary positional embeddings for local

00:03:35.514 --> 00:03:39.659
attention layers, and Proportional R-o-P-E for global layers. The combination

00:03:39.659 --> 00:03:43.803
is what enables reliably useful performance at two hundred fifty-six

00:03:43.803 --> 00:03:47.947
thousand tokens rather than just nominally supporting it. Third: Built-in

00:03:47.947 --> 00:03:52.092
Multimodal. Vision support is native across all four models —

00:03:52.092 --> 00:03:56.236
not a separate variant, baked into the base architecture. Audio

00:03:56.236 --> 00:04:00.381
support is available in the edge models. With Gemma three,

00:04:00.381 --> 00:04:04.525
if you wanted vision you got the vision model and

00:04:04.525 --> 00:04:08.670
made tradeoffs. With Gemma four, you just get vision. Now,

00:04:08.670 --> 00:04:12.814
the benchmarks — and an honest read of them. On

00:04:12.814 --> 00:04:16.959
M-M-L-U Pro: the thirty-one billion dense scores eighty-five point two

00:04:16.959 --> 00:04:21.103
percent. The twenty-six billion M-o-E scores eighty-two point six percent.

00:04:21.103 --> 00:04:25.248
The E-four-B scores sixty-nine point four percent. The E-two-B scores

00:04:25.248 --> 00:04:29.392
sixty percent. On G-P-Q-A Diamond — a hard reasoning benchmark

00:04:29.392 --> 00:04:33.537
— the thirty-one billion scores eighty-four point three percent. The

00:04:33.537 --> 00:04:37.682
twenty-six billion scores eighty-two point three percent. On A-I-M-E twenty

00:04:37.682 --> 00:04:41.826
twenty-six, competition math: the thirty-one billion scores eighty-nine point two

00:04:41.826 --> 00:04:45.971
percent. The twenty-six billion scores eighty-eight point three percent. Genuinely

00:04:45.971 --> 00:04:50.115
impressive numbers for an open model. On LMArena human preference

00:04:50.115 --> 00:04:54.260
rankings, the thirty-one billion dense sits at roughly number three

00:04:54.260 --> 00:04:58.404
among open models with an ELO score around fourteen fifty-two,

00:04:58.404 --> 00:05:02.548
ahead of Llama four Maverick. The twenty-six billion M-o-E holds

00:05:02.548 --> 00:05:06.693
an ELO around fourteen forty-one with only four billion parameters

00:05:06.693 --> 00:05:10.838
active. Legitimately strong numbers. But here's the honest part. The

00:05:10.838 --> 00:05:14.982
speed problem is real. Community benchmarks show the twenty-six billion

00:05:14.982 --> 00:05:19.126
M-o-E at roughly eleven tokens per second — where Qwen

00:05:19.126 --> 00:05:23.271
three-point-five thirty-five billion runs at sixty-plus. That's a five-times gap.

00:05:23.271 --> 00:05:27.416
For interactive applications, that's felt by every user. Chinese models

00:05:27.416 --> 00:05:31.560
remain competitive. On aggregate automated benchmarks, Qwen three-point-five, G-L-M-five, and

00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:35.704
Kimi K-two-point-five are at or slightly ahead. Gemma four genuinely

00:05:35.704 --> 00:05:39.849
outperforms in non-English multilingual tasks and human preference evaluations. But

00:05:39.849 --> 00:05:43.993
"Gemma four beats the Chinese models" is marketing copy. The

00:05:43.993 --> 00:05:48.138
reality is a close pack. And the two hundred fifty-six

00:05:48.138 --> 00:05:52.283
thousand token context window has caveats. Practically reaching that limit

00:05:52.283 --> 00:05:56.427
requires substantial V-R-A-M headroom. Your hardware will determine your practical

00:05:56.427 --> 00:06:00.571
limit. Running It on Your Mac. The E-four-B quantized to

00:06:00.571 --> 00:06:04.716
G-G-U-F is about nine point six gigabytes — fits a

00:06:04.716 --> 00:06:08.861
Mac mini M-four with room to spare. Using Ollama, the

00:06:08.861 --> 00:06:13.005
easiest option: you can run the E-two-B at about five

00:06:13.005 --> 00:06:17.149
point five gigabytes, E-four-B at nine point six gigabytes, the

00:06:17.149 --> 00:06:21.294
twenty-six billion M-o-E at eighteen gigabytes, or the thirty-one billion

00:06:21.294 --> 00:06:25.439
dense at twenty gigabytes. For faster performance on Apple Silicon,

00:06:25.439 --> 00:06:29.583
native M-L-X is the better path. And llama-dot-cpp works well

00:06:29.583 --> 00:06:33.727
if that's your preferred runtime. For hardware guidance: a MacBook

00:06:33.727 --> 00:06:37.872
Pro M-three with eighteen to thirty-six gigabytes of unified memory

00:06:37.872 --> 00:06:42.017
— the E-four-B runs well, twenty-six billion is possible at

00:06:42.017 --> 00:06:46.161
the high end. A Mac mini M-four Pro — E-four-B

00:06:46.161 --> 00:06:50.305
with headroom, twenty-six billion works at twenty-four gigabytes and up.

00:06:50.305 --> 00:06:54.450
A Mac Studio or M-three Ultra — all four variants

00:06:54.450 --> 00:06:58.594
comfortably. One important caveat: give the ecosystem a week before

00:06:58.594 --> 00:07:02.739
building anything serious. First-day Mac stability reports included some crashes

00:07:02.739 --> 00:07:06.884
and edge cases that should clear up quickly. Honest Assessment

00:07:06.884 --> 00:07:11.028
— What Actually Matters. Here's what actually matters — and

00:07:11.028 --> 00:07:15.172
it's not a benchmark number. The Apache two-point-zero license is

00:07:15.172 --> 00:07:19.317
the most important thing that happened on April second. Previous

00:07:19.317 --> 00:07:23.462
Gemma versions shipped with a custom Terms of Use that

00:07:23.462 --> 00:07:27.606
included monthly active user caps. Real teams encountered this and

00:07:27.606 --> 00:07:31.750
chose Mistral, Qwen, and Llama instead. Apache two-point-zero removes all

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:35.895
of that. No monthly active user caps. No acceptable-use restrictions.

00:07:35.895 --> 00:07:40.040
No royalties. Commercial teams can build on Gemma the same

00:07:40.040 --> 00:07:44.184
way they build on Llama — fully, without reservation. There's

00:07:44.184 --> 00:07:48.328
also a geopolitical angle: enterprise procurement teams are increasingly preferring

00:07:48.328 --> 00:07:52.473
U-S-origin A-I models for compliance and supply chain reasons. Gemma

00:07:52.473 --> 00:07:56.618
four being strong, Apache-licensed, and U-S-origin is genuinely useful positioning

00:07:56.618 --> 00:08:00.762
that benchmark tables don't capture. Now the gaps worth watching.

00:08:00.762 --> 00:08:04.906
First: fine-tuning ecosystem maturity. At launch, HuggingFace Transformers lacked full

00:08:04.906 --> 00:08:09.051
architecture support and P-E-F-T couldn't handle the new layer types.

00:08:09.051 --> 00:08:13.195
Give it a few weeks. Second: inference speed. Eleven versus

00:08:13.195 --> 00:08:17.340
sixty-plus tokens per second is a real product disadvantage. Either

00:08:17.340 --> 00:08:21.485
Google ships optimized inference kernels soon, or interactive applications will

00:08:21.485 --> 00:08:25.629
feel slow. Third: no mid-tier model. The gap between the

00:08:25.629 --> 00:08:29.773
E-four-B and twenty-six billion — where the Gemma three twelve

00:08:29.773 --> 00:08:33.918
billion lived — is real. There's no obvious successor to

00:08:33.918 --> 00:08:38.062
that sweet spot. Bottom Line. Let me bring this home

00:08:38.062 --> 00:08:42.207
with four specific situations. If you avoided Gemma because of

00:08:42.207 --> 00:08:46.351
the license restrictions — reconsider. Apache two-point-zero removes the blocker

00:08:46.351 --> 00:08:50.496
entirely. If you're evaluating for a new project — test

00:08:50.496 --> 00:08:54.640
the twenty-six billion M-o-E, but benchmark inference speed on your

00:08:54.640 --> 00:08:58.785
specific hardware first. The gap between theoretical and practical performance

00:08:58.785 --> 00:09:02.929
is wide right now. If you're interested in the architecture

00:09:02.929 --> 00:09:07.074
itself — the Per-Layer Embedding approach in the edge models

00:09:07.074 --> 00:09:11.219
is worth studying. Getting the quality of a much larger

00:09:11.219 --> 00:09:15.363
model at a fraction of the compute cost, through architectural

00:09:15.363 --> 00:09:19.507
cleverness rather than raw scale, is an important direction for

00:09:19.507 --> 00:09:23.652
the field. If you're looking for raw benchmark supremacy —

00:09:23.652 --> 00:09:27.796
the picture is mixed. It's a genuinely competitive frontier in

00:09:27.796 --> 00:09:31.941
April twenty twenty-six. The Apache two-point-zero move is Google choosing

00:09:31.941 --> 00:09:36.086
to fully participate in the open-weights ecosystem rather than hovering

00:09:36.086 --> 00:09:40.230
at its edge. That's the actual story here. The benchmarks

00:09:40.230 --> 00:09:44.375
are good. The architecture is interesting. But the license is

00:09:44.375 --> 00:09:48.519
what changes behavior. Thanks for listening to this Deep Dive.

00:09:48.519 --> 00:09:52.663
You can read the full written version, with benchmark tables

00:09:52.663 --> 00:09:56.808
and code examples, at the link in the show notes.
